# Basic Syntax

```csharp
try {
    int[] nums = {1, 2, 3};
    Console.WriteLine(nums[10]); // Error!
} 
catch (IndexOutOfRangeException ex) {
    Console.WriteLine("Index invalid!");
} 
catch (Exception ex) {
    Console.WriteLine("Something else wrong: " + ex.Message);
}
```

# Cleaning Up 🧹

Code in `finally` runs whether an exception happened or not. Perfect for closing files or database connections.

```csharp
try {
    // Open file...
} catch {
    // Handle error...
} finally {
    // Close file!
}
```

# Raising Errors 🚩

You can manually trigger exceptions using `throw`.

```csharp
public void SetAge(int age) {
    if (age < 0) {
        throw new ArgumentException("Age cannot be negative");
    }
    this.Age = age;
}
```

# Syntactic Sugar 🍬

Instead of manually closing resources in `finally`, use `using`. It automatically calls `Dispose()`.

```csharp
// Old way: try { ... } finally { file.Close(); }

// New way
using (StreamReader reader = new StreamReader("file.txt")) {
    Console.WriteLine(reader.ReadToEnd());
}
// 'reader' is automatically closed here!
```

